[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] CRFs are a type of discriminative undirected probabilistic graphical model.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] For general graphs, the problem of exact inference in CRFs is intractable.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] The inference problem for a CRF is basically the same as for an MRF and the same arguments hold.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] If exact inference is impossible, several algorithms can be used to obtain approximate solutions.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Learning the parameters $\theta$ is usually done by maximum likelihood learning for $p(Y_{i}|X_{i};\theta )$ .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] If all nodes have exponential family distributions and all nodes are observed during training, this optimization is convex.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] It can be solved for example using gradient descent algorithms, or Quasi-Newton methods such as the L-BFGS algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] On the other hand, if some variables are unobserved, the inference problem has to be solved for these variables.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Exact inference is intractable in general graphs, so approximations have to be used.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] In sequence modeling, the graph of interest is usually a chain graph.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] An input sequence of observed variables X represents a sequence of observations and Y represents a hidden (or unknown) state variable that needs to be inferred given the observations.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] The $Y_{i}$ are structured to form a chain, with an edge between each $Y_{i-1}$ and $Y_{i}$ .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] The conditional dependency of each $Y_{i}$ on X is defined through a fixed set of *feature functions* of the form $f(i,Y_{i-1},Y_{i},X)$ , which can be thought of as measurements on the input sequence that partially determine the likelihood of each possible value for $Y_{i}$ .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] The model assigns each feature a numerical weight and combines them to determine the probability of a certain value for $Y_{i}$ .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Linear-chain CRFs have many of the same applications as conceptually simpler hidden Markov models (HMMs), but relax certain assumptions about the input and output sequence distributions.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] An HMM can loosely be understood as a CRF with very specific feature functions that use constant probabilities to model state transitions and emissions.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Conversely, a CRF can loosely be understood as a generalization of an HMM that makes the constant transition probabilities into arbitrary functions that vary across the positions in the sequence of hidden states, depending on the input sequence.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Notably, in contrast to HMMs, CRFs can contain any number of feature functions, the feature functions can inspect the entire input sequence X at any point during inference, and the range of the feature functions need not have a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] CRFs can be extended into higher order models by making each $Y_{i}$ dependent on a fixed number k of previous variables $Y_{i-k},...,Y_{i-1}$ .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] In conventional formulations of higher order CRFs, training and inference are only practical for small values of k (such as *k* ≤ 5), since their computational cost increases exponentially with k .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] However, another recent advance has managed to ameliorate these issues by leveraging concepts and tools from the field of Bayesian nonparametrics.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Specifically, the CRF-infinity approach constitutes a CRF-type model that is capable of learning infinitely-long temporal dynamics in a scalable fashion.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] This is effected by introducing a novel potential function for CRFs that is based on the Sequence Memoizer (SM), a nonparametric Bayesian model for learning infinitely-long dynamics in sequential observations.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] To render such a model computationally tractable, CRF-infinity employs a mean-field approximation of the postulated novel potential functions (which are driven by an SM).
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] This allows for devising efficient approximate training and inference algorithms for the model, without undermining its capability to capture and model temporal dependencies of arbitrary length.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] There exists another generalization of CRFs, the **semi-Markov conditional random field (semi-CRF)**, which models variable-length *segmentations* of the label sequence Y .
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] This provides much of the power of higher-order CRFs to model long-range dependencies of the $Y_{i}$ , at a reasonable computational cost.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] Finally, large-margin models for structured prediction, such as the structured Support Vector Machine can be seen as an alternative training procedure to CRFs.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] In an LDCRF, like in any sequence tagging task, given a sequence of observations **x** = $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , the main problem the model must solve is how to assign a sequence of labels **y** = $y_{1},\dots ,y_{n}$ from one finite set of labels Y.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] This allows capturing latent structure between the observations and labels.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] While LDCRFs can be trained using quasi-Newton methods, a specialized version of the perceptron algorithm called the **latent-variable perceptron** has been developed for them as well, based on Collins' structured perceptron algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/conditional-random-field] These models find applications in computer vision, specifically gesture recognition from video streams and shallow parsing.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In this example, a person name consisting of one token, a two-token company name and a temporal expression have been detected and classified.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In the expression *named entity*, the word *named* restricts the task to those entities for which one or many strings, such as words or phrases, stand (fairly) consistently for some referent.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] This is closely related to rigid designators, as defined by Saul Kripke, although in practice NER deals with many names and referents that are not philosophically "rigid".
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] For instance, the *automotive company created by Henry Ford in 1903* can be referred to as *Ford* or *Ford Motor Company*, although "Ford" can refer to many other entities as well (see Ford).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Full named-entity recognition is often broken down, conceptually and possibly also in implementations, as two distinct problems: detection of names, and classification of the names by the type of entity they refer to (e.g. person, organization, or location).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The first phase is typically simplified to a segmentation problem: names are defined to be contiguous spans of tokens, with no nesting, so that "Bank of America" is a single name, disregarding the fact that inside this name, the substring "America" is itself a name.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] This segmentation problem is formally similar to chunking.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The second phase requires choosing an ontology by which to organize categories of things.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Temporal expressions and some numerical expressions (e.g., money, percentages, etc.) may also be considered as named entities in the context of the NER task.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] While some instances of these types are good examples of rigid designators (e.g., the year 2001) there are also many invalid ones (e.g., I take my vacations in “June”).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In the first case, the year *2001* refers to the *2001st year of the Gregorian calendar*.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In the second case, the month *June* may refer to the month of an undefined year (*past June*, *next June*, *every June*, etc.).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] It is arguable that the definition of *named entity* is loosened in such cases for practical reasons.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The definition of the term *named entity* is therefore not strict and often has to be explained in the context in which it is used.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Certain hierarchies of named entity types have been proposed in the literature.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] BBN categories, proposed in 2002, are used for *question answering* and consists of 29 types and 64 subtypes.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Sekine's extended hierarchy, proposed in 2002, is made of 200 subtypes.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] More recently, in 2011 Ritter used a hierarchy based on common Freebase entity types in ground-breaking experiments on NER over social media text.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] NER can have reference resolution ambiguities where the same name can refer to different entities of the same type.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] For example, "JFK" can refer to the former president of the United States or his son.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The same name can refer to completely different types.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] "JFK" might refer to the airport in New York.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] "IRA" can refer to Individual Retirement Account, International Reading Association or Irish Republican Army.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] For example, "The White House" can refer to an organization instead of a location.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] To evaluate the quality of an NER system's output, several measures have been defined.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The usual measures are called precision, recall, and F1 score.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] However, several issues remain in just how to calculate those values.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] These statistical measures work reasonably well for the obvious cases of finding or missing a real entity exactly; and for finding a non-entity.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] However, NER can fail in many other ways, many of which are arguably "partially correct", and should not be counted as complete success or failures.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] One overly simple method of measuring accuracy is merely to count what fraction of all tokens in the text were correctly or incorrectly identified as part of entity references (or as being entities of the correct type).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] It follows from the above definition that any prediction that misses a single token, includes a spurious token, or has the wrong class, is a hard error and does not contribute positively to either precision or recall.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Thus, this measure may be said to be pessimistic: it can be the case that many "errors" are close to correct, and might be adequate for a given purpose.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] For example, one system might always omit titles such as "Ms." or "Ph.D.", but be compared to a system or ground-truth data that expects titles to be included.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In that case, every such name is treated as an error.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Because of such issues, it is important actually to examine the kinds of errors, and decide how important they are given one's goals and requirements.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Evaluation models based on a token-by-token matching have been proposed.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Such models may be given partial credit for overlapping matches (such as using the Intersection over Union criterion).
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] They allow a finer grained evaluation and comparison of extraction systems.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] NER systems have been created that use linguistic grammar-based techniques as well as statistical models such as machine learning.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] State of the art systems may incorporate multiple approaches.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Hand-crafted grammar-based systems typically obtain better precision, but at the cost of lower recall and months of work by experienced computational linguists.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Statistical NER systems typically require a large amount of manually annotated training data.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Semisupervised approaches have been suggested to avoid part of the annotation effort.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In the statistical learning era, NER was usually performed by learning a simple linear regression model on engineered features, then decoded by a bidirectional Viterbi algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] A **gazetteer** is a list of names and their types, such as "General Electric".
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] It can be used to augment any system for NER.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] They had been often used in the era of statistical machine learning.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Many different classifier types have been used to perform machine-learned NER, with conditional random fields being a typical choice.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Transformers features token classification using deep learning models.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Early work in NER systems in the 1990s was aimed primarily at extraction from journalistic articles.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Attention then turned to processing of military dispatches and reports.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Later stages of the automatic content extraction (ACE) evaluation also included several types of informal text styles, such as weblogs and text transcripts from conversational telephone speech conversations.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Since about 1998, there has been a great deal of interest in entity identification in the molecular biology, bioinformatics, and medical natural language processing communities.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The most common entity of interest in that domain has been names of genes and gene products.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] There has been also considerable interest in the recognition of chemical entities and drugs in the context of the CHEMDNER competition, with 27 teams participating in this task.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In 2001, research indicated that even state-of-the-art NER systems were brittle, meaning that NER systems developed for one domain did not typically perform well on other domains.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Considerable effort is involved in tuning NER systems to perform well in a new domain; this is true for both rule-based and trainable statistical systems.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] As of 2007, state-of-the-art NER systems for English produce near-human performance.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] For example, the best system entering MUC-7 scored 93.39% of F-measure while human annotators scored 97.60% and 96.95%.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Despite high F1 numbers reported on the MUC-7 dataset, the problem of named-entity recognition is far from being solved.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] The main efforts are directed to reducing the annotations labor by employing semi-supervised learning, robust performance across domains and scaling up to fine-grained entity types.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] In recent years, many projects have turned to crowdsourcing, which is a promising solution to obtain high-quality aggregate human judgments for supervised and semi-supervised machine learning approaches to NER.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Another challenging task is devising models to deal with linguistically complex contexts such as Twitter and search queries.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] There are some researchers who did some comparisons about the NER performances from different statistical models such as HMM (hidden Markov model), ME (maximum entropy), and CRF (conditional random fields), and feature sets.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] And some researchers recently proposed graph-based semi-supervised learning model for language specific NER tasks.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] A recently emerging task of identifying "important expressions" in text and cross-linking them to Wikipedia can be seen as an instance of extremely fine-grained named-entity recognition, where the types are the actual Wikipedia pages describing the (potentially ambiguous) concepts.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] Another field that has seen progress but remains challenging is the application of NER to Twitter and other microblogs, considered "noisy" due to non-standard orthography, shortness and informality of texts.
[src:named-entity-recognition/named-entity-recognition] NER challenges in English Tweets have been organized by research communities to compare performances of various approaches, such as bidirectional LSTMs, Learning-to-Search, or CRFs.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Major processing tasks in an NLP system include: speech recognition, text classification, natural language understanding, and natural language generation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Natural language processing has its roots in the 1950s.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Already in 1950, Alan Turing published an article titled "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," which proposed what is now called the Turing test as a criterion of intelligence, though at the time that was not articulated as a problem separate from artificial intelligence.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] The proposed test includes a task that involves the automated interpretation and generation of natural language.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Up until the 1980s, most natural language processing systems were based on complex sets of hand-written rules.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Starting in the late 1980s, however, there was a revolution in natural language processing with the introduction of machine learning algorithms for language processing.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Symbolic approach, i.e., the hand-coding of a set of rules for manipulating symbols, coupled with a dictionary lookup, was historically the first approach used both by AI in general and by NLP in particular: such as by writing grammars or devising heuristic rules for stemming.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] In the late 1980s and mid-1990s, the statistical approach ended a period of AI winter, which was caused by the inefficiencies of the rule-based approaches.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] The earliest decision trees, producing systems of hard if–then rules, were still very similar to the old rule-based approaches.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Only the introduction of hidden Markov models, applied to part-of-speech tagging, announced the end of the old rule-based approach.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] A major drawback of statistical methods is that they require elaborate feature engineering.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Since 2015, neural network–based methods have increasingly replaced traditional statistical approaches, using semantic networks and word embeddings to capture semantic properties of words.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Intermediate tasks (e.g., part-of-speech tagging and dependency parsing) are not needed anymore.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Neural machine translation, based on the then-newly invented sequence-to-sequence transformations, made obsolete the intermediate steps, such as word alignment, previously necessary for statistical machine translation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] The following is a list of some of the most commonly researched tasks in natural language processing.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Some of these tasks have direct real-world applications, while others more commonly serve as subtasks that are used to aid in solving larger tasks.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Though natural language processing tasks are closely intertwined, they can be subdivided into categories for convenience.
