[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] , marketed as a novel, contains sixty million words.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] , this is grounded on factual knowledge and based on text summarization.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] A Document AI platform sits on top of the NLP technology enabling users with no prior experience of artificial intelligence, machine learning or NLP to quickly train a computer to extract the specific data they need from different document types.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] NLP-powered Document AI enables non-technical teams to quickly access information hidden in documents, for example, lawyers, business analysts and accountants.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Computer systems intended to converse with a human.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Given a human-language question, determine its answer.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Typical questions have a specific right answer (such as "What is the capital of Canada?"), but sometimes open-ended questions are also considered (such as "What is the meaning of life?").
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Given a description of an image, generate an image that matches the description.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:named-entity-recognition/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In corpus linguistics, **part-of-speech tagging** (**POS tagging**, **PoS tagging**, or **POST**), also called **grammatical tagging**, is the process of marking up a word in a text (corpus) as corresponding to a particular part of speech, based on both its definition and its context.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] A simplified form of this is commonly taught to school-age children, in the identification of words as nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, etc.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Once performed by hand, POS tagging is now done in the context of computational linguistics, using algorithms which associate discrete terms, as well as hidden parts of speech, by a set of descriptive tags.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] POS-tagging algorithms fall into two distinctive groups: rule-based and stochastic.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Brill's tagger, one of the first and most widely used English POS taggers, employs rule-based algorithms.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Part-of-speech tagging is harder than just having a list of words and their parts of speech, because some words can represent more than one part of speech at different times, and because some parts of speech are complex.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] This is not rare—in natural languages (as opposed to many artificial languages), a large percentage of word-forms are ambiguous.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Correct grammatical tagging will reflect that "dogs" is here used as a verb, not as the more common plural noun.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Schools commonly teach that there are 9 parts of speech in English: noun, verb, article, adjective, preposition, pronoun, adverb, conjunction, and interjection.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] However, there are clearly many more categories and sub-categories.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For nouns, the plural, possessive, and singular forms can be distinguished.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In many languages words are also marked for their "case" (role as subject, object, etc.), grammatical gender, and so on; while verbs are marked for tense, aspect, and other things.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In some tagging systems, different inflections of the same root word will get different parts of speech, resulting in a large number of tags.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, NN for singular common nouns, NNS for plural common nouns, NP for singular proper nouns (see the POS tags used in the Brown Corpus).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Other tagging systems use a smaller number of tags and ignore fine differences or model them as features somewhat independent from part-of-speech.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In part-of-speech tagging by computer, it is typical to distinguish from 50 to 150 separate parts of speech for English.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Work on stochastic methods for tagging Koine Greek (DeRose 1990) has used over 1,000 parts of speech and found that about as many words were ambiguous in that language as in English.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] A morphosyntactic descriptor in the case of morphologically rich languages is commonly expressed using very short mnemonics, such as *Ncmsan* for Category = Noun, Type = common, Gender = masculine, Number = singular, Case = accusative, Animate = no.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The most popular "tag set" for POS tagging for American English is probably the Penn tag set, developed in the Penn Treebank project.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] It is largely similar to the earlier Brown Corpus and LOB Corpus tag sets, though much smaller.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In Europe, tag sets from the Eagles Guidelines see wide use and include versions for multiple languages.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] POS tagging work has been done in a variety of languages, and the set of POS tags used varies greatly with language.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Tags usually are designed to include overt morphological distinctions, although this leads to inconsistencies such as case-marking for pronouns but not nouns in English, and much larger cross-language differences.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The tag sets for heavily inflected languages such as Greek and Latin can be very large; tagging *words* in agglutinative languages such as Inuit languages may be virtually impossible.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] At the other extreme, Petrov et al. have proposed a "universal" tag set, with 12 categories (for example, no subtypes of nouns, verbs, punctuation, and so on).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Whether a very small set of very broad tags or a much larger set of more precise ones is preferable, depends on the purpose at hand.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Automatic tagging is easier on smaller tag-sets.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Research on part-of-speech tagging has been closely tied to corpus linguistics.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The first major corpus of English for computer analysis was the Brown Corpus developed at Brown University by Henry Kučera and W.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] It consists of about 1,000,000 words of running English prose text, made up of 500 samples from randomly chosen publications.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Each sample is 2,000 or more words (ending at the first sentence-end after 2,000 words, so that the corpus contains only complete sentences).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The Brown Corpus was painstakingly "tagged" with part-of-speech markers over many years.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] A first approximation was done with a program by Greene and Rubin, which consisted of a huge handmade list of what categories could co-occur at all.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, article then noun can occur, but article then verb (arguably) cannot.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Its results were repeatedly reviewed and corrected by hand, and later users sent in errata so that by the late 70s the tagging was nearly perfect (allowing for some cases on which even human speakers might not agree).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] This corpus has been used for innumerable studies of word-frequency and of part-of-speech and inspired the development of similar "tagged" corpora in many other languages.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Statistics derived by analyzing it formed the basis for most later part-of-speech tagging systems, such as CLAWS and VOLSUNGA.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] However, by this time (2005) it has been superseded by larger corpora such as the 100 million word British National Corpus, even though larger corpora are rarely so thoroughly curated.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For some time, part-of-speech tagging was considered an inseparable part of natural language processing, because there are certain cases where the correct part of speech cannot be decided without understanding the semantics or even the pragmatics of the context.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] This is extremely expensive, especially because analyzing the higher levels is much harder when multiple part-of-speech possibilities must be considered for each word.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In the mid-1980s, researchers in Europe began to use hidden Markov models (HMMs) to disambiguate parts of speech, when working to tag the Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus of British English.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs involve counting cases (such as from the Brown Corpus) and making a table of the probabilities of certain sequences.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, once you've seen an article such as 'the', perhaps the next word is a noun 40% of the time, an adjective 40%, and a number 20%.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Knowing this, a program can decide that "can" in "the can" is far more likely to be a noun than a verb or a modal.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The same method can, of course, be used to benefit from knowledge about the following words.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] More advanced ("higher-order") HMMs learn the probabilities not only of pairs but triples or even larger sequences.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] So, for example, if you've just seen a noun followed by a verb, the next item may be very likely a preposition, article, or noun, but much less likely another verb.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] When several ambiguous words occur together, the possibilities multiply.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] However, it is easy to enumerate every combination and to assign a relative probability to each one, by multiplying together the probabilities of each choice in turn.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The combination with the highest probability is then chosen.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The European group developed CLAWS, a tagging program that did exactly this and achieved accuracy in the 93–95% range.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS pioneered the field of HMM-based part of speech tagging but was quite expensive since it enumerated all possibilities.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] It sometimes had to resort to backup methods when there were simply too many options (the Brown Corpus contains a case with 17 ambiguous words in a row, and there are words such as "still" that can represent as many as 7 distinct parts of speech.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs underlie the functioning of stochastic taggers and are used in various algorithms one of the most widely used being the bi-directional inference algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Church independently developed dynamic programming algorithms to solve the same problem in vastly less time.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Their methods were similar to the Viterbi algorithm known for some time in other fields.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose used a table of pairs, while Church used a table of triples and a method of estimating the values for triples that were rare or nonexistent in the Brown Corpus (an actual measurement of triple probabilities would require a much larger corpus).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Both methods achieved an accuracy of over 95%.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose's 1990 dissertation at Brown University included analyses of the specific error types, probabilities, and other related data, and replicated his work for Greek, where it proved similarly effective.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] These findings were surprisingly disruptive to the field of natural language processing.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The accuracy reported was higher than the typical accuracy of very sophisticated algorithms that integrated part of speech choice with many higher levels of linguistic analysis: syntax, morphology, semantics, and so on.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS, DeRose's and Church's methods did fail for some of the known cases where semantics is required, but those proved negligibly rare.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] This convinced many in the field that part-of-speech tagging could usefully be separated from the other levels of processing; this, in turn, simplified the theory and practice of computerized language analysis and encouraged researchers to find ways to separate other pieces as well.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Markov Models became the standard method for the part-of-speech assignment.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The methods already discussed involve working from a pre-existing corpus to learn tag probabilities.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] It is, however, also possible to bootstrap using "unsupervised" tagging.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Unsupervised tagging techniques use an untagged corpus for their training data and produce the tagset by induction.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] That is, they observe patterns in word use, and derive part-of-speech categories themselves.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, statistics readily reveal that "the", "a", and "an" occur in similar contexts, while "eat" occurs in very different ones.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] With sufficient iteration, similarity classes of words emerge that are remarkably similar to those human linguists would expect; and the differences themselves sometimes suggest valuable new insights.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] These two categories can be further subdivided into rule-based, stochastic, and neural approaches.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Some current major algorithms for part-of-speech tagging include the Viterbi algorithm, Brill tagger, Constraint Grammar, and the Baum-Welch algorithm (also known as the forward-backward algorithm).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Hidden Markov model and visible Markov model taggers can both be implemented using the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] The rule-based Brill tagger is unusual in that it learns a set of rule patterns, and then applies those patterns rather than optimizing a statistical quantity.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Many machine learning methods have also been applied to the problem of POS tagging.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Methods such as SVM, maximum entropy classifier, perceptron, and nearest-neighbor have all been tried, and most can achieve accuracy above 95%.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] A direct comparison of several methods is reported (with references) at the ACL Wiki.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] This comparison uses the Penn tag set on some of the Penn Treebank data, so the results are directly comparable.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] However, many significant taggers are not included (perhaps because of the labor involved in reconfiguring them for this particular dataset).
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] Thus, it should not be assumed that the results reported here are the best that can be achieved with a given approach; nor even the best that *have* been achieved with a given approach.
[src:named-entity-recognition/part-of-speech-tagging] In 2014, a paper reported using the structure regularization method for part-of-speech tagging, achieving 97.36% on a standard benchmark dataset.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:named-entity-recognition/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] In linguistics and natural language processing, a **corpus** (pl.: **corpora**) or **text corpus** is a dataset, consisting of natively digital and older, digitalized, language resources, either annotated or unannotated.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Annotated, they have been used in corpus linguistics for statistical hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] A corpus may contain texts in a single language (*monolingual corpus*) or text data in multiple languages (*multilingual corpus*).
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] In order to make the corpora more useful for doing linguistic research, they are often subjected to a process known as annotation.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] An example of annotating a corpus is part-of-speech tagging, or *POS-tagging*, in which information about each word's part of speech (verb, noun, adjective, etc.) is added to the corpus in the form of *tags*.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Another example is indicating the lemma (base) form of each word.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] When the language of the corpus is not a working language of the researchers who use it, interlinear glossing is used to make the annotation bilingual.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Some corpora have further *structured* levels of analysis applied.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] In particular, smaller corpora may be fully parsed.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Such corpora are usually called Treebanks or Parsed Corpora.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] The difficulty of ensuring that the entire corpus is completely and consistently annotated means that these corpora are usually smaller, containing around one to three million words.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Other levels of linguistic structured analysis are possible, including annotations for morphology, semantics and pragmatics.
[src:named-entity-recognition/text-corpus] Corpora are the main knowledge base in corpus linguistics.
